   "source": [
    "The Local Approach partitions the spatial domain into a grid and runs point-based DBSCAN independently within each cell. To avoid missing clusters that span cell boundaries, an **epsilon-buffer** layer is added: points within `EPS` degrees of a cell edge are copied to neighbouring cells before clustering. After all cells are processed independently, a **Union-Find boundary merge** step stitches together cluster fragments that were split across cell edges.\n",
    "\n",
    "This implementation uses a **directional buffer** (inspired by RP-DBSCAN, Lee et al.) rather than copying every point to all 8 neighbours. Only points near a relevant edge are copied in the corresponding direction, reducing data duplication from ~9x down to ~2.14x. Clustering is then run at four data scales (5%, 10%, 25%, 100%) to assess scalability.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Pipeline:**\n",
    "1. Assign grid cells and compute directional boundary flags\n",
    "2. Union buffered + original DataFrames, repartition by `grid_cell_id`\n",
    "3. Run `point_dbscan_per_cell` via `applyInPandas` on each partition\n",
    "4. Boundary merge using Union-Find to resolve cross-cell cluster fragments\n",
    "\n",
    "**Per-cell optimisations:**\n",
    "- If a cell exceeds 10,000 points, a random subsample is taken before DBSCAN runs to prevent executor OOM on the densest Beijing cells (max 302,702 points). The cap rarely triggers on 5%, 10%, or 25% subsets.\n",
    "- Coordinates are cast to `float32` before ball_tree construction, halving the memory footprint of the coordinate array per partition compared to the default `float64`, without affecting clustering correctness at the spatial resolution used (ε = 0.0045°)."
   ]
  },
