   "source": [
    "The Global Approach partitions the spatial domain into a uniform grid and runs point-based DBSCAN independently within each cell, with **no epsilon buffer**. Instead of pre-expanding partitions, cross-partition connectivity is reconstructed explicitly through a distributed border-point comparison step.\n",
    "\n",
    "Each cell is processed in isolation: labels are encoded as `cell_id × 10⁶ + local_label` to prevent cross-worker collisions. Points within `EPS` of any cell edge are flagged as **border points** and passed to the merge step.\n",
    "\n",
    "The core contribution is **Stage 3**: a distributed self-join across neighbouring cells identifies border-point pairs within `EPS`, signalling clusters that require merging. A full join is infeasible at scale (~1M × ~1M rows), so border points are randomly sampled to 200 per cluster per cell boundary, sufficient by the MR-DBSCAN merge-point theorem, which guarantees one density-reachable pair establishes connectivity. Stage 4 resolves canonical labels via Union-Find on the driver and propagates them to workers via broadcast join, replacing an initial UDF that took 546 seconds.\n",
    "\n",
    "All results below use `MAX_POINTS_PER_CELL_GLOBAL = 20,000`, applied at the Spark layer before data reaches Python workers.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Pipeline:**\n",
    "1. Load subset → assign grid cells → apply Spark-level cap (Stage 1)\n",
    "2. Per-cell DBSCAN via `applyInPandas` with globally unique label encoding (Stage 2)\n",
    "3. Distributed border-point self-join across neighbouring cells (Stage 3)\n",
    "4. Union-Find merge on driver → broadcast join to propagate final labels (Stage 4)"
   ]
  },
